Ask HN: How much do you value reverse engineering skills when hiring?
text: It seems like there’s a trend from big corps to hire engineers who can grind leetcode. But I’ve seen another trend that I think is much more powerful: hiring people who are good at reverse engineering. I’m not talking anout binary RE, rather being able to look at some spaghetti undocumented code and figure out what it does or add tests and refactor it

Show HN: Can You Draw the Perfect Circle?
text:
Hey everyone,

I saw a post couple of weeks ago here (https://neal.fun/perfect-circle/) and got inspired to implement ShapeN, a minimalist mobile game that challenges you to draw a perfect circle. I kind of spiced it up with some levels and a high score table to make it more engaging.

iOS: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/shapen/id1670577699 Android: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.erenalgan....

Once you've downloaded the game, give it a try and see if you can draw the perfect circle and pass the levels. You can post your score in the comments and let me know how you did!

Feedback is welcome!

PS: No, I'm not the student in this video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZeoNYoL0ys0) but I invited them to take the challenge :P

Thanks for your time :)

Ask HN: Keyboard friendly search engine for developers?
text:
I recently switched to Vim key bindings in all my text editors. I found out that I can do most of the things from keyboard directly. The bigger pain point as of now is Googling stuff. I can switch to Chrome and search on Google all from keyboard. That is all fine. Problem is that when I'm searching terms like "filename from pathlib Path" I'm searching for one line example. I'd love to have a search engine which is geared towards programmers that can show me the results directly from the search, without having to click any link.

Requirements are: - decent search results - either show the answer directly or allow me to jump to the first result from keyboard
